\section{Fold Events and the Black-Hole / Fluid-Wave Analogy}

The classical black-hole singularity in general relativity is re-interpreted in TOGT as a macroscopic fold ($F$) in spacetime contact structure. Gravitational collapse drives compression ($C$), extreme curvature twists the Reeb flow ($K$), and the point of divergent curvature marks the geometric fold.

The fluid-dynamics analog of converging concentric waves forming a vertical spike provides a laboratory-scale visualization of the identical $C \to K \to F$ sequence \citep{barcelo2011analogue,braunstein2024analogue}. In nuclear physics this corresponds to:
- Density waves in heavy-ion collisions leading to quark-gluon plasma compression.
- Subsequent fold-like transitions during hadronization.
- Stabilization via the entropic boundary (event-horizon analog or causal isolation in dense matter).

Such analogs are directly testable in analogue gravity experiments with superfluids or Bose-Einstein condensates \citep{braunstein2024analogue}.

\section{Fractal Measure and Stability Threshold in Nuclear Matter}

The geometric weight $\eta^{-k}$ induces the fractal measure $\mu_\eta$ on $\ker\alpha$. Self-similar scaling appears in:
- Power spectra of collective excitations in quark-gluon plasma \citep{depman2020fractals,ding2023fractal}.
- Multiplicity distributions in high-energy collisions.
- Coherent structures in nuclear pasta or neutron-star crust (at $g \approx 33$ lock-in).

The stability threshold $g=33$ predicts characteristic lengths in nuclear matter where orthogenetic cycles stabilize into observable hadronic or collective modes, consistent with lattice-QCD calculations of nuclear binding \citep{beane2010nuclear,savage2012nuclear}.

\section{Falsifiability Conditions}

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{W.1}: Deviation from $\eta^{-k}$ weighting in multiplicity or transverse-momentum spectra must exceed standard QCD predictions in heavy-ion data (e.g., LHC or RHIC) \citep{chandra2025multifractal}.
\item \textbf{F.1}: Fold events must correlate with measurable spikes in flow harmonics or jet quenching patterns, reproducible in fluid-analogue simulations \citep{braunstein2024analogue}.
\item \textbf{$\Phi$.1}: Fractal time-crystal-like resonances (or power-law spectra with Tribonacci spacing) must appear in photon or dilepton emission from quark-gluon plasma \citep{depman2020fractals}.
\item \textbf{AXLE}: All operator compositions and measure definitions are formally verified in Lean 4.
\end{enumerate}

These predictions are distinguishable from pure perturbative QCD or standard hydrodynamics.

\section{Conclusion}

TOGT supplies a unified geometric language for strong-interaction dynamics: contact 3-manifolds provide the backbone, the Reeb flow supplies orthogenetic time, and the dm$^3$ cycle with Tribonacci scaling generates self-similar nuclear structures through iterated fold events. Macroscopic singularities and fluid-wave analogs confirm the universality of the operator grammar \citep{schutzhold2002gravity,braunstein2024analogue}.

The framework is falsifiable with existing and forthcoming heavy-ion, lattice QCD, and analogue-gravity data \citep{beane2010nuclear,deForcrand2010nuclear}. It offers a bottom-up, operator-driven complement to QCD at non-perturbative nuclear scales.

\section*{Acknowledgements}
All algebraic derivations were verified via the AXLE engine. Numerical explorations used standard Tribonacci implementations.

